2ï¸âƒ£ Types of Health Probes

Kubernetes has three probes:

Liveness Probe

Readiness Probe

Startup Probe

Each has a different purpose.

3ï¸âƒ£ Liveness Probe (Is the app stuck?)
What it checks

ğŸ‘‰ Is the application still alive and responsive?

If liveness probe fails repeatedly:
â¡ Kubernetes restarts the container.

When to use

App can hang or deadlock

Memory leaks

App is running but not responding

Example (HTTP)
livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 8080
  initialDelaySeconds: 10
  periodSeconds: 10


If /health returns non-200, container is restarted.

Real-life example

App is running but thread is stuck â†’ liveness fails â†’ container restarted â†’ app recovers.

4ï¸âƒ£ Readiness Probe (Can it receive traffic?)
What it checks

ğŸ‘‰ Is the app ready to serve requests right now?

If readiness probe fails:
â¡ Pod is removed from Service endpoints
â¡ No restart happens

When to use

App is warming up

DB connection not ready

Cache not loaded

Example
readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /ready
    port: 8080
  initialDelaySeconds: 5
  periodSeconds: 5


If readiness fails:

Traffic stops

Pod stays running

Real-life example

DB goes down â†’ readiness fails â†’ pod stops receiving traffic â†’ users donâ€™t see errors.

5ï¸âƒ£ Startup Probe (Has the app started?)
Why it exists

Some apps start very slowly.
Liveness probe might kill them before startup completes.

Startup probe tells Kubernetes:
ğŸ‘‰ Wait until startup is complete before applying liveness checks.

How it works

Startup probe runs first

Once it succeeds:

Startup probe stops

Liveness & readiness start

Example
startupProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 8080
  failureThreshold: 30
  periodSeconds: 10


This gives the app:
ğŸ‘‰ 30 Ã— 10 = 300 seconds to start.

6ï¸âƒ£ Full Example (All Probes Together)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: probe-demo
spec:
  containers:
    - name: app
      image: myapp
      ports:
        - containerPort: 8080

      startupProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /health
          port: 8080
        failureThreshold: 30
        periodSeconds: 10

      livenessProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /health
          port: 8080
        periodSeconds: 10

      readinessProbe:
        httpGet:
          path: /ready
          port: 8080
        periodSeconds: 5

7ï¸âƒ£ What happens internally (Flow)
Container starts
   â†“
Startup Probe checks
   â†“
Startup successful
   â†“
Readiness Probe (traffic control)
   â†“
Liveness Probe (restart control)

8ï¸âƒ£ Key Differences (Very Important)
Probe	Purpose	Failure Result
Startup	App started?	Container killed if exceeded
Readiness	Can serve traffic?	Removed from service
Liveness	App alive?	Container restarted
9ï¸âƒ£ Interview one-liners ğŸ¯

Liveness: Restarts stuck containers

Readiness: Controls traffic flow

Startup: Protects slow-starting apps

Kubernetes uses probes to determine container health, readiness to receive traffic, and when to restart applications safely.
